We conducted the study at 12 courts and found that the focus group meetings were a welcome addition to the legal proceedings at these courts when it concerned divorce. The members of the committee [committee for resolving conflict involved in divorce cases] supervised by the courts perform a double role in that they sit at a court that deals specifically with cases of divorce but they fill a much broader role of dealing with disputes on a wider platform [...] Often, even where the couple had reached some form of resolution, the community members who contributed to the process remained concerned about the long term situation until the final forms of divorce were lodged at the courts.
Morgan Matandadzimba, Chief Executive Officer of the Community Media Trust (Organisation that advised the Study) [87]

2.4 Analysis of the 2014 data

In 2014, ICCO decided to include divorce conditions that were linked to Title 19, Chapter 20 of the Divorce Act^59 in the list of Articles against which the sanctions should be set in the Index.
